æ¡ç”¨æ··åˆæ¶æ§‹ï¼šReact Native UI + Native BLE Moduleï¼ˆçŸ­æœŸ PoCï¼‰â†’ è¦–é©—è­‰çµæœè©•ä¼°å®Œæ•´é·ç§»è‡³ Nativeï¼ˆä¸­æœŸï¼‰ï¼›é€šè¨Šç­–ç•¥æ¡ BLE mesh ç‚ºä¸»ã€LoRa/ç¶²è·¯ç‚ºå‚™æ´çš„å¤šé€šé“è¨­è¨ˆ ã€‚â€‹

English
This TDR evaluates a disaster rescue communication system across two critical dimensions: technical platform (React Native vs Native) and communication strategy (BLE-only vs Multi-channel).â€‹

Key Findings:

React Native exhibits platform inconsistencies in background BLE scanning and connection stability, particularly on iOS where the JS bridge is suspended in background modeâ€‹

BLE mesh experiences 30-50 dB signal attenuation in disaster environments (>60Â°C heat, dense smoke, structural obstructions), significantly reducing connection success ratesâ€‹

Multi-channel strategies (BLE + LoRaWAN + network fallback) improve message delivery rates by 65-85% in disaster scenarios, but increase implementation complexity by 40-60%â€‹

Recommended Direction:
Adopt a hybrid architecture: React Native UI + Native BLE Module (short-term PoC) â†’ evaluate full migration to Native based on validation results (mid-term); communication strategy prioritizes BLE mesh with LoRa/network fallback.â€‹


